      <div class="curriculum-contents">
        <div class="kinder-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>We teach the mechanics of reading–students and explicit phonics instruction. Students are taught
            spelling, grammar, and writing. These are the primary tools for decoding written English. Students will
            learned all of the sound‐spelling correspondences in the English language and are able to decode written
            material they encounter.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Listening</li>
            <li>Nursery Rhymes</li>
            <li>Stories</li>
            <li>Spelling/Forming words</li>
            <li>Blending syllable</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>The first day of kindergarten is long anticipated by parents and young students. The goal of kindergarten
            math curriculum is to prepare children for first grade math.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Counting and place value</li>
            <li>Addition and subtraction</li>
            <li>Measurement and geometry</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="first-content">
           <h5>ELA</h5>
           <p>First-grade language art builds on the skills of writing and reading,
             which all should be learned by the end of kindergarten.
             We move them from reading readiness to actual reading skills.
             It also aims to expand their written skills from letters and
             words to complete sentences and complex thoughts.</p>
           <ul>
             <li>Recognize digraphs, sound blends, diphthongs</li>
             <li>Pronounce word endings</li>
             <li>Create group of rhyming words</li>
             <li>Count the number of syllables in words</li>
             <li>Spelling words, identify contractions</li>
             <li>Decipher meaning of words</li>
           </ul>
           <h5>Math</h5>
           <p>Math for first grade curriculum are number sense and operations,
             algebra, geometry and spatial sense, measurement, and data analysis
             and probability. They are all critical lessons for first grade
             math curriculum.</p>
           <ul>
             <li>Place value</li>
             <li>Numbers 0 to 120</li>
             <li>Ones and tens</li>
             <li>Addition within 20</li>
             <li>Subtraction within 20</li>
             <li>Time</li>
             <li>Length and size</li>
           </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="second-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>Second grade english is more progress in reading and language arts. Second graders will be reading and understanding language arts with more developing vocabulary words. They will be writing competently. Second grade students are expected to be progressive in development of reading comprehension.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Developing more word vocabulary</li>
            <li>Using punctuation appropriately</li>
            <li>Experiencing a variety of literary genres</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>Second grade will start exploring numbers in the real world around us - understanding the use of money in
            real life situations. Second grade will focus on solving problems involving addition and subtraction and more.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Hundreds</li>
            <li>Adding 1s and 10s</li>
            <li>Substracting 1s and 10s</li>
            <li>Addition with 100 and 1000</li>
            <li>Subtraction within 100 and 1000</li>
            <li>Money</li>
            <li>Word problems</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="third-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>Third graders learn prewriting strategy. In this grade, they will now understand the formula for writing process. Third grade is the first step in learning how to write for a particular audience. They will expand more in vocabulary to create more in-depth sentences. They will be reading more with fluency and with focus on comprehension</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Prewriting strategy</li>
            <li>Formula writing process</li>
            <li>Write more persuasively</li>
            <li>Write more in-depth sentences</li>
            <li>Focus reading comprehension</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>Third grade is the year of better math skill development. They will now learn how to multiply and divide with multi-digit numbers by a single-digit number. At this point, they will understand simple fractions and decimals.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Multiplication</li>
            <li>Division</li>
            <li>Estimation</li>
            <li>Fractions/Decimals</li>
            <li>Area</li>
            <li>Perimeter</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="fourth-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>Fourth grade is the year of higher progress in reading, writing and language arts. Reading in fourth grade is higher level of fluency and expression. Students will utilize root words, prefixes, suffixes, and context clues to analyze unfamiliar words. They will apply comprehension strategies to literary texts. Focus on cause and effect.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Higher level of fluency</li>
            <li>Root words, prefixes, suffixes, and context clues</li>
            <li>Comprehension strategies to literary texts</li>
            <li>Formulate multiple paragraph</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>Fourth grade deals with bigger numbers. They will add and subtract large numbers with sums up to 1,000,000. They will
          complete basic multiplication and division problems. Understand more basic fraction and decimal concepts.
          They will recognize and identify more basic geometrical vocabulary.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Write expanded form and written form</li>
            <li>Rounding whole numbers</li>
            <li>Adding and subtracting multi-digit numbers</li>
            <li>Multiply 2-digit numbers</li>
            <li>Division with place value</li>
            <li>Factors and mulitples</li>
            <li>Prime and Composite numbers</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="fifth-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>We teach 5th graders on how to apply comprehension strategies to literary texts. They will understand literary techniques such as summarizing, plot identification, main idea, theme, cause and effect, compare and contrast, fact vs. opinion, and making inferences.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Proficiency is reading skills</li>
            <li>Comprehension strategies to literary genres</li>
            <li>Main Idea vs. Theme</li>
            <li>Understanding Author's purpose</li>
            <li>Write appropriately in composition assignments</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>Fifth graders should be proficient using addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. They will learn basic algebraic functions such as exponents and order of operations. Apply geometric concepts to solve problems, and use various methods of measurement with skill.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Decimal place value</li>
            <li>Adding and subtracting decimals</li>
            <li>Common denominators</li>
            <li>Adding and subtracting fractions with unlike denominatros</li>
            <li>Adding and subtracting mix numbers</li>
            <li>Multiply/Dividing fractions</li>
            <li>Algebra</li>
            <li>Volume</li>
            <li>Multiply and Divide decimals</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sixth-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>In 6th grade, students explore more comprehensive reading texts. 6th graders will have better understanding in writing and reading. They will read closely to textual details. They will make evidence-based argument essays. They will be searching literary texts to have deepen understanding of english literacy.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Writing better evidence based essays</li>
            <li>Finding contextual evidence in literary texts</li>
            <li>Further searching for themes and main idea of literary texts</li>
            <li>Deeper understanding of literary arts</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>6th grade is the first year of middle school, and they will get introduced to new mathematic problems. It is the first year for students to learn mathematics that are usually primer to prepare them for high school. Students will more complex fractions, decimals, exponents and pre-algebra.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Ratios, rates, & percentages</li>
            <li>Arithmetic operations</li>
            <li>Adding, subtracting, dividing, and multiplying decimals</li>
            <li>Exponents</li>
            <li>Least and Greatest common factor</li>
            <li>Negative numbers</li>
            <li>Equations & inequlaties</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="seventh-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>Seventh grader will develop more complex writing skills.
            They will write constructive critique of their own and other’s writing. Improve grammar, and syntax skills.
            They will read with fluency, with focus on comprehension.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Improve complex writing skills</li>
            <li>Improve writing syntax skills</li>
            <li>Apply and recognize grade standard vocabulary</li>
            <li>Read with focus on comprehension</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>7th grade math students will be expected to learn the order of operations to solve problems using
          parenthesis, exponents, multiplication, division, addition and subtraction. They will learn about
          proportional relationships using tables, graphs, and “constant ratio” relationships to solve and explain problems.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Additing, subtracting, multiplying and dividing negative numbers</li>
            <li>Converting fractions to decimals</li>
            <li>Percentages</li>
            <li>Adding & subtracting ration numbers</li>
            <li>Rates & proportional relationships</li>
            <li>Expressions, equations, & inequlaties</li>
            <li>Order of operations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="eigth-content">
          <h5>ELA</h5>
          <p>8th grade is the last year before they are entered into highschool. Our agenda for 8th graders is to prepare themselves academically before they reach 9th grade. We teach proficiency in grade standards to ensure that students be prepared and ready in literacy before their last year of middle school.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Students gain more comprehension to evaluate complex information, ideas, and evidence</li>
            <li>Formal english writing that can be recognize by high school instructors</li>
            <li>Write logical arguments based on author's claims</li>
            <li>Improve explanatory texts and narratives</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Math</h5>
          <p>Students continue to hone their skill of solving equations. 8th grade students will become more efficient in math. Solve equations in one variable. At this point 8th grade will become well equiped to be ready for high school.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Numbers and operations</li>
            <li>Solve equations with on variable</li>
            <li>Linear functions and equations</li>
            <li>Systems of equations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

